I recently hit a turning point in my SQL learning — and it wasn’t about syntax, it was about thinking.

One concept that really challenged me was understanding the difference between:
• Overall average
• Average per customer

At first, they looked similar. But they operate at completely different levels.

Overall average works at the order level — one value for the entire dataset.
Average order value works at the customer level — one value per customer.

Mixing these up leads to incorrect results, even if the SQL runs fine.

Another key learning was when to use window functions vs subqueries.

Window functions are powerful, but not always the answer.
Sometimes a simple scalar subquery or CTE is the correct approach — especially when dealing with global metrics.

The biggest shift for me was this:

SQL is not about writing queries.
It’s about understanding the level of data you’re working with.

If you get the “grain” right, the query becomes much simpler.

Now focusing on:
• Window functions (ranking, running totals)
• Writing interview-level SQL
• Thinking in data layers instead of just syntax

Would love to hear — what SQL concept took you the longest to truly understand?
